{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01TauNgYVDGWUwKysafCAfcE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate exactly 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me break down the requirements:\n\n1. Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.22.txt`\n2. Filename rules:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens/underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Title in filename must match title in content (case-insensitive)\n\n3. Recipe mix: ~60% English, ~40% Polish\n4. Variety of categories and title lengths\n5. Must be DIFFERENT from the existing list provided\n\n6. Pattern requirements:\n   - 5 files with SIMPLE: basic OCR noise (stray numbers, page headers, broken words)\n   - 3 files with OCR_CORRUPTION: misrecognized characters throughout\n   - 2 files with NARRATIVE: 3-7 lines of prose intro\n\n7. File length: 15-60 lines, spillover files longer\n\nLet me create a diverse set:\n\n**SIMPLE FILES (5):**\n1. English - Tomato Basil Soup\n2. Polish - Piernik z Miodem (Honey Gingerbread)\n3. English - Lentil Walnut Soup\n4. Polish - Żabka Pieczona (Roasted Frog - wait, that's weird, maybe Żabka w Pomidorach but that's taken. Let me pick something else)\n5. English - Wild Mushroom Tart\n\nActually, let me look at the existing list again to avoid duplicates. I need to be careful.\n\nExisting English: ARAYES SHRAK, Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander, Faszerowana papryka, OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH, FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS, KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA, Chleb Żytni, LEMON CURD : LEMON CURD WITH THYME, Makowiec, Peach Cobbler, Bigos Jesienny z Grzybami, Smażone Pierniki, RYE BREAD WITH CARAWAY + RYE BREAD WITH SUNFLOWER SEEDS, Che Cheesecake z Jeżynami, Kluski Śląskie ze Szpinakiem, Bigos Letni, Chrust, Whipped Goat Cheese Dip, Braised Cod with White Wine, Lavender Panna Cotta, Golonka, Garlic Mushroom Risotto, Kopytka z Grzybami, Bigos z Grzybami, Obwarzanek Warszawski, Żurek Krakowski, Mushroom Risotto, Bigos Myśliwski, Roasted Chicken with Root Vegetables, Tomato Basil Soup is already there. I need to pick something completely different.\n\nLooking at the next batch, I see several pasta dishes like Creamy Mushroom Pasta and Tomato Basil Pasta, various soups including Żurek Litewski, Żurek Śląski, and Żurek, plus traditional Polish baked goods like Piernik Tradycyjny, Babka Drożdżowa, and Sernik Malinowy ze Czekoladą. There are also herb-forward mains like Herb Roasted Pork with Mushrooms and Herb Crusted Lamb Chops, alongside lighter options like Beet Arugula Salad and Sweet Potato Salad. I'm noticing several recipes are already in the existing collection, so I need to find alternatives that feel authentic without duplicating. Let me consider some fresh options: Smalec Zwyczajny, Żurek ze Zbożem, Kotłety Szare, or simpler dishes like Piernik z Rabarbarem and Kluski z Masłem could work well. I'll create a new set of recipes that sound genuine but aren't already included in the list.\n\nI'm planning ten recipes across different styles and languages. For the Polish dishes, I'm mixing in variations like Bigos Jesienny z Żółtą Kapustą and Kapusniak Obfity, while the English recipes include options like Creamy Fennel Soup, Pan Seared Scallops with Herb Butter, and Grilled Seabass with Fennel. I'm assigning different complexity levels—some marked as SIMPLE, others as OCR_CORRUPTION or NARRATIVE—to create variety in the collection.\n\nI notice there's some overlap with root vegetables, so I'm adjusting the English entry from \"Roasted Root Vegetable Medley\" to \"Roasted Parsnips with Thyme\" to avoid duplication. The Polish recipes are getting longer treatments, ranging from 30 to 50 lines, while the English ones sit between 22 and 45 lines. I'm also refining some titles—changing \"Piernik Miodowy z Czekoladą\" to \"Piernik Miodowy z Orzechami\" and \"Spiced Apple Cake with Walnuts\" to \"Spiced Apple Cake with Cardamom\" for better distinction.\n\nLooking at the full list, I realize several recipes are too similar in concept. I'm pivoting toward more variety: replacing some of the root vegetable and seafood entries with Brussels Sprouts and Bacon Soup, Żurek Białostocki, Sole with Brown Butter and Capers, and Kopytka with mushrooms and dill. This gives better balance across different cooking techniques and flavor profiles.\n\nFor the final selections, I'm settling on a mix that spans soups, mains, and desserts across both languages—Brussels Sprouts and Bacon Soup, Żurek Białostocki, Sole with Brown Butter and Capers, Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Sernik z Malinami i Białą Czekoladą, and Cranberry Orange Tart. I need to complete the eighth entry and verify the ninth and tenth don't duplicate existing recipes.\n\nLooking at what's already included, I notice several categories appearing repeatedly—soups, gingerbread variations, hunter's stew, and dumplings. To create better variety, I should pull from these established categories but with distinct flavor profiles rather than introducing entirely new dish types.\n\nThe reorganized list breaks down into clear sections: soups featuring Brussels sprouts with bacon, Żurek Białostocki, and root vegetables; main courses with sole in brown butter and capers, mushroom kopytka, and halibut with saffron; desserts and baked goods including raspberry cheesecake with white chocolate, cranberry orange tart, and spiced gingerbread; plus roasted asparagus with Parmesan as a side component.\n\nNow I'll generate the actual recipe content, incorporating realistic OCR artifacts. For the corruption patterns, I'll use digit substitutions like 'só1' instead of 'sól', dotless characters, hyphenation breaks, and garbled tokens. The simpler entries will have page numbers, section labels, and marginal numbers with occasional character noise. The narrative-style recipes will span multiple lines with more extensive formatting variations. sprouts and broth, bring to boil. Reduce heat and simmer 20 minutes until sprouts are tender. Stir in cream and nutmeg, season with salt and pepper, then blend if a smoother texture is preferred. Top with bacon bits and fresh thyme, serves 4-6.\n\nFor the Polish żurek, I'm working with rye soup starter, kielbasa, and young cabbage as the base. The ingredient list includes potatoes, onions, butter, caraway and marjoram for seasoning, plus bay leaves and fresh dill for garnish. The preparation starts by heating butter and sautéing onions for 5 minutes, then browning the sliced kielbasa for 3 minutes before adding the rye starter and bringing everything to a boil.\n\nNow moving to the sole dish - this is a classic preparation with brown butter and capers. The fillets are paired with browned butter, drained capers, minced shallots, sliced garlic, dry white wine, and fresh lemon juice to create a bright, savory sauce. til nutty aroma develops, about 4-5 minutes. Stir in capers and almonds, then return the sole to the pan and coat it thoroughly with the sauce. Let it cook for another minute before serving immediately, garnished with fresh parsley. The recipe yields 4 servings.\n\nFor the Polish kopytka dish, I need potatoes, wheat flour, an egg, fresh mushrooms sliced into chunks, diced onions, minced garlic, sunflower oil, sage, salt and pepper, plus fresh dill for garnish. The preparation starts by cooking the potatoes until tender, draining them well, then mashing while still warm before combining with flour and egg.\n\nI form small oval dumplings from the mixture. In a separate pan, I sauté sage in oil, add the mushrooms and cook for about 5 minutes. The kopytka go into boiling salted water—once they float to the surface, I add the onion and garlic to the mushroom mixture. Everything gets tossed together and served hot with fresh dill on top, making 4 portions.\n\nThe asparagus dish is straightforward but refined—fresh spring vegetables roasted until tender-crisp. I heat the oven to 425°F, coat the trimmed asparagus with olive oil, garlic, salt and pepper, then spread it on a baking sheet for 12-15 minutes. After roasting, I finish it with grated parmesan, lemon zest, and red pepper flakes for a final 2 minutes in the oven, then garnish with basil and serve immediately while still warm, enough for 4-6 people.\n\nIn Polish culinary tradition, sernik holds a special place. This classic dessert with medieval roots combines delicate fresh cheese with raspberries and white chocolate sweetness. The author's grandmother made this every summer when raspberries peaked, and now each bite carries childhood memories and the scent of summer. The recipe begins with a crust made from ground butter cookies, melted butter, and sugar.\n\nFor the filling, fresh cheese is beaten smooth with sugar, then combined with melted white chocolate, eggs, vanilla extract, lemon zest, and salt. Fresh raspberries are folded in gently. The crust mixture is pressed into a 23cm springform pan, and the filling is poured over before baking until set. it with a special touch. The buttery crust, smooth custard, and glossy cranberries create a striking combination that's memorable. This works well for holiday tables or formal dinners.\n\nFor the pastry, I need flour, cold butter, egg yolk, ice water, salt, and sugar. The filling requires fresh or frozen cranberries, orange zest and juice, sugar, custard powder, milk, egg yolks, and butter. There's also an orange glaze to finish it.\n\nTo prepare, I'll blend the dry ingredients, work in the cold butter until crumbly, then add the egg yolk and water to form dough. After chilling, I'll roll it out for the tart pan, prick the base, and blind bake it. For the custard, I'll whisk yolks with sugar, heat the milk and combine them, then cook with custard powder until thickened. Once I fold in the orange zest, juice, and butter, I'll pour it into the crust, top with cranberries, and bake until set. A final brush of warm marmalade glaze brings everything together.\n\nLet it cool fully before slicing. This makes 8 servings.\n\nFor this Polish bigos with plums and bacon, gather 800g of fresh or packaged cabbage, 300g of sliced kielbasa, 200g of diced bacon, 400g of fresh or dried plums, 2 chopped onions, 4 minced garlic cloves, 2 bay leaves, 1 teaspoon caraway seeds, 2 tablespoons oil, salt and pepper, and 1 cup broth. Heat the oil in a large pot, fry the bacon until crispy, then sauté the onion and garlic for a few minutes before adding the remaining ingredients. I need to steep the saffron threads in hot water for 10 minutes to extract their flavor. Heat butter and olive oil in a pan over medium-high heat, then season the halibut fillets with salt and white pepper before cooking them 4-5 minutes per side until they're cooked through. Remove the fish and set aside to keep warm. In the same pan, sauté the diced shallots until they soften, then deglaze with white wine and reduce it by half before adding the cream and saffron infusion.\n\nLet the sauce simmer for a few minutes until it thickens slightly, then return the halibut to coat it in the sauce. Plate and finish with fresh dill and a lemon wedge. This makes 4 servings.\n\nFor the Polish spiced honey cake, combine honey and sugar over low heat, cool briefly, then mix in butter and eggs. In another bowl, whisk together flour, baking soda, cinnamon, cardamom, ground cloves, nutmeg, salt, and orange zest before folding into the wet ingredients.\n\nPour the batter into a greased 23x33cm pan and bake at 180°C for 35-40 minutes until a wooden pick comes out clean. Once cooled, dust with powdered sugar and cut into 12-15 squares.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":90156,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":90156},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"s